{{also|Abigail}}
==English==

===Etymology===
From the name {{m|en|Abigail}}, as given to a waiting-maid in Beaumont and Fletcher's play ''{{w|The Scornful Lady}}''.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˈa.bɪ.ɡeɪl/|lang=en}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|/ˈa.bɪ.ɡeɪl/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{label|en|obsolete}} A [[lady]]’s [[waiting maid]]. {{defdate|Mid 17<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref>{{R:SOED5|page=4}}</ref>
#* {{quote-book|year=1749|author=Henry Fielding|title=Tom Jones|page=415|passage=It was therefore concluded that the '''Abigails''' should, by turns, relieve each other on one of his lordship’s horses, which was presently equipped with a side-saddle for that purpose.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1847|author=Charlotte Brontë|title=Jane Eyre|passage=In the servants’ hall two coachmen and three gentlemen’s gentlemen stood or sat round the fire; the '''abigails''', I suppose, were upstairs with their mistresses; the new servants, that had been hired from Millcote, were bustling about everywhere.}}

